import matplotlib as plt
fig, ax = plt.pyplot.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches(10.5, 6)
N=52016
form1 = {'family': 'serif', 'color': 'Blue', 'size': 12}
x = np.arange(1,N+1,1)
y = df2['CumulativePercent']
ax.plot(x, y, color='black')
plt.pyplot.xlabel("Rank",fontdict=form1)
plt.pyplot.ylabel("CumulativePercent",fontdict=form1)
plt.pyplot.title("The 20% of the workers that bring 84% of Revenue ",fontdict=form1)
threshold = 84
ax.axhline(threshold, color='green', lw=3, alpha=0.9)
ax.fill_between( x,0.81, where=(y < threshold), color='green', alpha=0.3, transform=ax.get_xaxis_transform(),
                label='20% of the Workers')

Recency, frequency, monetary value (RFM) is a marketing analysis tool used to identify a firm's best clients based on the nature of their spending habits. Recency: How recently a worker has made a revenue (Last_revenue_date) Frequency: How often a worker makes a revenue (total_revenue_line) Monetary Value: How much money a worker make (TotalRevenue)

#make RFM table 
rfmTable = df2.groupby('id').agg({'hist': lambda x:x.min(), # Recency
                                        'TotalRevenue': lambda x: x.sum()})# Monetary Value

rfmTable.rename(columns={'hist': 'recency', 
                         'TotalRevenue': 'monetary_value'}, inplace=True)

#standardize the recency and monetary_value 

#Date from customer's last purchase.The nearest date gets 5 and the furthest date gets 1.
rfmTable["recency_score"] = pd.qcut(rfmTable['recency'], 5, labels=[5, 4, 3, 2, 1])

#Total spend by the customer.The least money gets 1, the most money gets 5.
rfmTable["monetary_score"]= pd.qcut(rfmTable["monetary_value"], 5, labels=[1,2,3,4,5])

#categorize our workers based on recency and monetary value

seg_map = {
    r'[1-2][1-2]': 'hibernating',
    r'[1-2][3-4]': 'at_Risk',
    r'[1-2]5': 'cant_loose',
    r'3[1-2]': 'about_to_sleep',
